---
title: "Why Support Chatbots Frustrate Users: The Psychology Behind Poor Conversation Flow"
date: "2024-07-23"
summary: "Chatbots frustrate users when the conversation flow violates conversational expectations. Design for the human, not for the bot."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Behavioral Psychology"
author: "Redevise"
---

A user enters a chatbot. They type their question. The bot does not understand. The user rephrases. The bot does not understand. The user is frustrated.

The frustration is not about the bot's intelligence. It is about the conversation flow. Humans have expectations about conversations. Turn-taking. Context. Progress. When a bot violates these expectations, the user is frustrated.

Here are the violations.

No context retention. The user provides information. The bot asks for it again. The user expects the bot to remember. The bot does not. The user is frustrated.

No progress. The user does not know if the bot is working. No "thinking." No "checking." No progress indicator. The user is uncertain. Uncertainty is frustration.

No escape. The user wants to talk to a human. The bot does not offer a path. The user is trapped. Trapping is frustration.

I redesigned a client's chatbot in 2024. The old bot had no context retention. No progress indicators. No escape path. The satisfaction score was 2.1 out of 5. The new bot had all three. The satisfaction score was 3.8 out of 5.

The teams that design for the bot are the ones with frustrated users. The teams that design for the human are the ones with satisfied users.

Retain context. Show progress. Offer escape. The frustration fades.
